- an event that is not a tuple;
- first element not "set" or "del" (including an empty tuple);
- wrong number of elements for its op;
- ts not an int, or ts < 0; booleans are NOT acceptable timestamps (True/False must raise even though bool is a subclass of int);
- key not a str.

Then fold: events apply in ascending timestamp order. For events sharing the same timestamp: all "set" events at that timestamp apply first, in input-list order (so for the same key the set appearing later in the list wins), then all "del" events at that timestamp apply (so a del beats every set at the same timestamp for the same key, regardless of input order). A del for an absent key is a silent no-op. A set at a strictly later timestamp than a del re-creates the key.

